\name{Supp}
\alias{Supp}
\alias{Initth}
\alias{Energy}
\title{Subordinate functions to run the t-walk algorithm for the posterior function}
\usage{
Supp(th)

Initth()

Energy(th)
}
\arguments{
\item{th}{numeric vector of length = lenght(mu) + (ncol(A)*(ncol(A)+1)/2)}
}
\value{
\code{Supp} equals TRUE, if valid values of mu and A are contained
  in the vector th, and FALSE, if one or both parameters are out of the
  support of the objective function.
  \code{Initth} returns a numeric vector such that its length is equal to\eqn{lenght(mu)
  +(ncol(A)*(ncol(A)+1)/2)} and contains initial values for mu and A.
  \code{Energy} returns -log of the posterior function at \code{th}.
}
\description{
These three functions are used when the t-walk algorithm is used to simulate
values from the posterior function and estimate the centroid (mu) and the
 precision matrix (A) that define a fundamental niche. If the undelying
statistical model changes, these functions must be modified.
}
\details{
Details: in case of a bivariate normal distribution, length(mu)=2 and
ncol(A)=3 then length(th) = 2 + (2*3)/2 = 5 (degrees of freedom).
}
\section{Functions}{
\itemize{
\item \code{Supp}: Evaluates if its argument is within the support of the
posterior function.

\item \code{Initth}: Produces initial values within the support of the posterior
function.

\item \code{Energy}: Evaluates the posterior distribution.
}}

